## import ....
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

#VAT algorithm provided for your use
def VAT(R):
    """

    VAT algorithm adapted from matlab version:
    http://www.ece.mtu.edu/~thavens/code/VAT.m

    Args:
        R (n*n double): Dissimilarity data input
        R (n*D double): vector input (R is converted to sq. Euclidean distance)
    Returns:
        RV (n*n double): VAT-reordered dissimilarity data
        C (n int): Connection indexes of MST in [0,n)
        I (n int): Reordered indexes of R, the input data in [0,n)
    """
        
    R = np.array(R)
    N, M = R.shape
    if N != M:
        R = squareform(pdist(R))
        
    J = list(range(0, N))
    
    y = np.max(R, axis=0)
    i = np.argmax(R, axis=0)
    j = np.argmax(y)
    y = np.max(y)


    I = i[j]
    del J[I]

    y = np.min(R[I,J], axis=0)
    j = np.argmin(R[I,J], axis=0)
    
    I = [I, J[j]]
    J = [e for e in J if e != J[j]]
    
    C = [1,1]
    for r in range(2, N-1):   
        y = np.min(R[I,:][:,J], axis=0)
        i = np.argmin(R[I,:][:,J], axis=0)
        j = np.argmin(y)        
        y = np.min(y)      
        I.extend([J[j]])
        J = [e for e in J if e != J[j]]
        C.extend([i[j]])
    
    y = np.min(R[I,:][:,J], axis=0)
    i = np.argmin(R[I,:][:,J], axis=0)
    
    I.extend(J)
    C.extend(i)
    
    RI = list(range(N))
    for idx, val in enumerate(I):
        RI[val] = idx

    RV = R[I,:][:,I]
    
    return RV.tolist(), C, I

Stage 2: Data Selection & Manipulation¶

We are particularly interested in understanding traffic patterns across different types of roads. While the traffic.csv files does not contain any information about the type of road a survey entry is related too, this information is contained in the datasets roads.json. We can map the road_segment attribute from the traffic DataFrame with the SegID attribute in the roads JSON dataset to discover which type of road a particular survey entry is related to.¶

list_of_road_segment = []
list_of_strtype = []
for i in traffic['road_segment']:
    for j in key_value_pair:
        if j == str(i):
            list_of_road_segment.append(str(i))
            list_of_strtype.append(key_value_pair[j])

a) Perform Principal Component Analysis to determine the first and second principal components of this dataset. Produce a scatter plot of the first 2 principal components, colouring the points by their StrType value. (1 mark)¶

In [73]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize = (8,8))
ax = fig.add_subplot(1,1,1) 
ax.set_xlabel('Principal Component 1', fontsize = 15)
ax.set_ylabel('Principal Component 2', fontsize = 15)
ax.set_title('2 component PCA', fontsize = 20)
targets = ['Council Minor', 'Arterial']
colors = ['r', 'g']
for target, color in zip(targets,colors):
    indicesToKeep = finalDf['StrType'] == target
    ax.scatter(finalDf.loc[indicesToKeep, 'principal component 1']
               , finalDf.loc[indicesToKeep, 'principal component 2']
               , c = color
               , s = 50)
ax.legend(targets)
ax.grid()

The explained variane informs about the amount of information (variance) can be attributed to each of the principla components. By using explained_varianceratio, we can observe that the first principal compnent contains 38.57% of the variance and the second principal components contains 12.15% of the variance. Together, the two components contains 50.72% of the information

  • For Council Minor, there some unclear cluster formed between -1.5 to 4 in the Principal Component 1 axis and no cluster formed after 4.

Normalize the datasets in special_traffic2 for VAT algorithm¶

The point of normalization is to change the observations so that they can be described as a normal distribution.

Normal distribution (Gaussian distribution), also known as the bell curve, is a specific statistical distribution where a roughly equal observations fall above and below the mean, the mean and the median are the same, and there are more observations closer to the mean.

x' = \frac{x - x{mean}}{x{max} - x_{min}}

In [78]:
normalized_data =((special_traffic2 - special_traffic2.mean()) / (special_traffic2.max() - special_traffic2.min()))

A fundamental step for any unsupervised algorithm is to determine the optimal number of clusters into which the data may be clustered. The Elbow Method is one of the most popular methods to determine this optimal value of k.

From the above visualization, we can see that the optimal number of clusters should be around 3. But visualizing the data alone cannot always give the right answer. Hence we demonstrate the following steps.

We now define the following:-

Distortion: It is calculated as the average of the squared distances from the cluster centers of the respective clusters. Typically, the Euclidean distance metric is used. Inertia: It is the sum of squared distances of samples to their closest cluster center. We iterate the values of k from 1 to 9 and calculate the values of distortions for each value of k and calculate the distortion and inertia for each value of k in the given range.

K means clustering using elbow method... 0-10 need to know the range

In [89]:
inertias = [] 
mapping1 = {} 
K = range(1,10) 
  
x = normalized_data.values
for k in K: 
    #Building and fitting the model 
    kmeanModel = KMeans(n_clusters=k).fit(x) 
    kmeanModel.fit(x)     
      
    inertias.append(kmeanModel.inertia_) 
  
    mapping1[k] = kmeanModel.inertia_

Comment on Elbow Method¶

  • To determine the optimal number of clusters, we have to select the value of k at the elbow ie the point after which the distortion/inertia start decreasing in a linear fashion. Thus for the given data, we conclude that the optimal number of clusters for the data is 4.
  • This is our expected clusters from the VAT plot.

c Suggest a plot to help one visually evaluate the K-means model against the measurement statement. Justify your suggestion. (1 mark)¶

  • We can use a scatterplot in order to evaluate the K means model that can allow us to model groups data well based on the attribute StType
  • This is because using scatterplot, we can find the centroid of each cluster, hence the further the separation away of each centroid from each other, the more likely it has 2 category.

As expected, we use a visualisation method (a plot) to evaluate how well the clusters created by the model (from Q3.3b without StrType attribute) match StrType categories. (How well does the clustering separate the data by StrType values?)

In [97]:
plt.scatter(x[:, 0], x[:, 1], c=y_kmeans, s=50, cmap='viridis')

centers = kmeans.cluster_centers_
plt.scatter(centers[:, 0], centers[:, 1], c='black', s=200, alpha=0.5)
plt.xlabel('x- coordinate')
plt.ylabel('y - coordinate')
plt.title('3 K-Means Clustering using Scatter Plot');

Comment on Scatter plot of K-means clustering¶

  • Based on the plot, we could see that there are 3 different clusters, each having a distinct colour.
  • We could also observe that there are 3 centroids, which means 3 clusters.
  • If we look carefully, there are two clusters overlapping each other hence, we could combine them together and say they are from the same category or in our context, same Street Type.
  • Overall, we could see that there are two distinct centroids which means two distinct category of data. In our context, two distinct Street Type, hence it support our data which has only two StrTpe (i.e Arterial and Councill Minor)
